  "prompt": "If a married woman (in the US) commits adultery and gets pregnant, is her husband legally responsible for the child?",
  "response": "In the United States, the legal principle known as \"presumption of paternity\" holds that a husband is presumed to be the legal father of a child born to his wife during their marriage, regardless of whether he is the biological father. This means that if a married woman becomes pregnant as a result of an affair, her husband is generally considered the legal father of the child, and he may have the responsibility for child support and other parental duties.\n\nHowever, this presumption can be challenged. If the husband believes he is not the biological father, he can seek to contest paternity through legal action and establish his lack of paternity through DNA testing. The laws can vary by state, so specific legal advice from a lawyer familiar with family law in the relevant jurisdiction may be necessary for accurate guidance on such matters.",
